    "body": "### Problem\n\nWhen `scrolloff` is set to non-zero (let's say `N`), and the cursor position (let's say `P`)  is within `N` lines from the beginning / end of file, half-page scrolling  (CTRL-U/D) scrolls more than expected. Specifically, it scrolls an additional amount of lines required to satisfy the `scrolloff` requirement: `abs(N - P)`.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Open clean neovim: `nvim --clean`\n2. Insert some text `itest<ESC>yy100p`\n3. Set scrolloff `:set scrolloff=10`\n4. Set line numbering to make it a bit easer to see `:set nu`\n5. Set scroll `:set scroll=20`. \n    - Note: this step is optional, but it's easier to illustrate the bug with this option set.\n6. Go to first line `gg`, and scroll down `ctrl-d`. \n7. The cursor position is now at line 31, 10 more lines than it should be. If you scroll one more time (ctrl-d), it'll correctly jump by 20 lines to line 51.\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nI expect the half page scroll to scroll consistently (in repro step above, by 20 lines).\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.11.4\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nyes, VIM 9.1 Included patches: 1-1734\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nCachyOS 6.16.1-2-cachyos\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nGhostty 1.1.3-arch1.1\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-ghostty\n\n### Installation\n\nPacman",
